additional class reading:


Sohn, M.D., M.J. Small, and M. Pantazidou, Reducing uncertainty in site characterization using Bayes Monte Carlo
methods, Journal of Environmental Engineering-Asce, 126 (10), 893-902, 2000.




papers:

Efron, B. 1986. Why Isn't Everyone a Bayesian?. American Statistician 40 (1):1-5.

Urban, N., M. and K. Keller: Complementary observational constraints on climate sensitivity,
Geophysical Research Letters, (2009).

Ricciuto, D. M., K. J. Davis, and K. Keller: A Bayesian synthesis inversion of carbon cycle
observations: How can observations reduce uncertainties about future sinks? Global
Biogeochemical Cycles, 22, doi:10.1029/2006GB002908 (2008).

Urban, N. M. and K. Keller, Probabilistic hindcasts and projections of the coupled climate,
carbon cycle, and Atlantic meridional overturning circulation systems: A Bayesian fusion of
century-scale observations with a simple model, Tellus A, in review (2009)

Qian, S. S., C. A. Stow, and M. E. Borsuk. 2003. On Monte Carlo methods for Bayesian
inference. Ecological Modelling 159 (2-3):269-277.

Hargreaves, J. C., and J. D. Annan. 2002. Assimilation of paleo-data in a simple Earth system
model. Climate Dynamics 19 (5-6):371-381.

Kheshgi, H. S., A. K. Jain, and D. J. Wuebbles. 1999. Model-based estimation of the global
carbon budget and its uncertainty from carbon dioxide and carbon isotope records. Journal of
Geophysical Research-Atmospheres 104 (D24):31127-31143.

Draper, D. 1995. Assessment and Propagation of Model Uncertainty. Journal of the Royal
Statistical Society Series B-Methodological 57 (1):45-97.

Kelly, D. L., and C. D. Kolstad. 1999. Bayesian learning, growth and pollution. Journal of
Economic Dynamics and Control 23:491-518.



